<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">Find your deployment</h3>

<p class="govuk-body">
  The Text-to-Speech scenario deployed via CloudFormation. Let's find your stack and access the Polly console:
</p>

<ol class="govuk-list govuk-list--number govuk-list--spaced">
  <li>
    <strong>Open the CloudFormation console</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      Go to <a href="https://us-east-1.console.aws.amazon.com/cloudformation/home?region=us-east-1#/stacks" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="govuk-link">CloudFormation console (us-east-1 N. Virginia)</a>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Find your stack</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      Look for a stack named <code>ndx-try-text-to-speech-[timestamp]</code> with status <strong>CREATE_COMPLETE</strong>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Click the Outputs tab</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      Select your stack, then click the "Outputs" tab. You'll see a list of resources created by the deployment.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Open the Polly console URL</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      Find the output key <code>PollyConsoleURL</code> and click the URL value. This opens the Amazon Polly
      text-to-speech interface with pre-configured permissions.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>

<div class="govuk-inset-text">
  <p class="govuk-body">
    <strong>What's happening:</strong> The CloudFormation stack created an S3 bucket for audio storage
    and configured IAM permissions for Polly access. The console URL includes embedded credentials so
    you do not need to manage AWS permissions manually.
  </p>
</div>

